The mandibular process of each side fuses during embryological development at the mandibular symphysis, forming a single continuous bone known as the mandible. While both sides contribute to the structure of the lower jaw, specifically the body and ramus, the term "lower jaw" refers directly to the formed mandible. Although the lower lip is anatomically related via sensory nerves like the inferior alveolar nerve, it is not derived from the fusion of mandibular processes. Therefore, the correct answer reflects the primary structural outcome of fusion—the lower jaw—rather than a soft-tissue derivative like the lower lip.

